  <div class="body">

  <p class="lead">Every year, headlines announce what the average American worker earned. Every year, that number is technically accurate and practically useless. Average wages are a ratio — total compensation divided by total earners. When earnings at the very top grow dramatically faster than earnings everywhere else, the average rises even when most workers fall behind. The average is not lying to you. It is simply answering a different question than you think you are asking.</p>

  <p>This field study uses Social Security Administration (SSA) earnings data, as analyzed by Elise Gould and Jori Kandra of the Economic Policy Institute, to examine what actually happened to wages at different points in the distribution between 1979 and 2021. The SSA data has one significant advantage over most wage surveys: it is not top-coded. Most household survey data assigns a common ceiling to reported high earnings — effectively capping what can be measured at the top. The SSA data reports actual W-2 earnings, which means the distance between the top and everyone else can be measured honestly.</p>

  <p>The answer is striking. And it is directly relevant to how any analyst, manager, or executive should think about distribution when they pick a summary statistic for their reports.</p>

  <h2>What happened to wages between 1979 and 2021</h2>
  <span class="h2-sub">Four decades of divergence</span>

  <p>Start with the headline numbers. Between 1979 and 2021, wages for workers in the bottom 90% grew approximately 29% in real (inflation-adjusted) terms. Over that same 42-year period, wages for the top 1% grew roughly 179%. Wages for the top 0.1% grew 465%.</p>

