  <p>These are not small statistical differences. The top 0.1% grew at roughly 16 times the rate of the bottom 90%. Over 40 years, a 16-to-1 divergence in compounding growth rates produces a gap that is difficult to fully grasp as a single number — which is precisely why most reporting avoids the distribution and reaches for the average instead.</p>

  <div class="pullquote">
    <p>The average wage tells you what the total compensation pool would be if it were split equally. It does not tell you how it was actually split.</p>
  </div>

  <h2>The share of the pie</h2>
  <span class="h2-sub">How the distribution of total earnings shifted</span>

  <p>Growth rates tell one story. Changes in share of total earnings tell another — and in some ways a cleaner one, because it removes the noise of overall economic expansion and asks a direct question: who captured the gains?</p>

  <p>In 1979, the top 1% of earners claimed about 7.3% of all wages. By 2021, that share had doubled to 14.6% — a record high. In the same period, the bottom 90%'s share fell from 69.8% to 58.6%, a historic low.</p>

