  <p>Within that top 1%, the concentration is even more striking at the very apex. The top 0.1% of earners held 1.6% of total wages in 1979. By 2021 that figure had reached 5.9% — roughly 3.7 times higher. Of the entire 7.3 percentage point increase in the top 1% share, about 4.3 percentage points — nearly 60% — came from the top 0.1% alone. The concentration of wage gains has not been evenly distributed even within the top.</p>

  <h2>What 2021 looked like year-over-year</h2>
  <span class="h2-sub">The pandemic data adds a sharp illustration</span>

