  <p>Wages for the top 0.1% rose 18.5% in a single year — real, inflation-adjusted earnings growth — at the same time most of the workforce absorbed real losses. In a given year, the average wage could easily show modest overall growth while concealing that the distribution was moving sharply in opposite directions simultaneously.</p>

  <h2>Why this is a measurement story, not just an economics story</h2>
  <span class="h2-sub">What the wage data reveals about how summary statistics work</span>

  <p>The wage inequality data makes a point that extends well beyond economics. It is a clean illustration of what any analyst should know about averages: they compress distributions into a single value, and in doing so, they erase the most interesting and consequential information about how the underlying data actually behaves.</p>

  <div class="callout">
    <p><strong>The data quality angle most reports miss:</strong> The SSA earnings data used in this research is non-top-coded. Standard household survey data caps reported income at a common maximum to protect privacy — meaning wages above that ceiling are all assigned the same value. This makes high-end inequality structurally unmeasurable from typical survey sources. The gap between the top 0.1% and everyone else is systematically undercounted in most published wage analyses.</p>
    <p>This is not a minor footnote. The top-coding problem means that <em>decades</em> of wage research using household survey data understated the concentration at the top. The SSA data, by using actual W-2 records, shows a distribution that is more concentrated at the peak than standard sources imply.</p>
  </div>

  <p>The same dynamic appears in business reporting constantly. A company reports average sales per rep and management concludes that performance is broadly acceptable. Meanwhile, two top performers account for 60% of revenue, and the lower half of the team is producing results that would fail any objective threshold. The average absorbed the variance and returned a number that answered none of the decision-relevant questions.</p>

  <p>Or consider customer lifetime value, churn rates, or time-to-close metrics. Each of these is routinely reported as an average. Each has a distribution that typically contains information far more useful than the central tendency — outliers, clusters, floor effects, ceiling effects. When the distribution is skewed or bimodal, the mean is often the least informative summary statistic available.</p>

  <div class="pullquote">
    <p>When a distribution is skewed, the mean tells you where the weight is — not where most of the people are.</p>
  </div>

  <h2>What the data says about causes</h2>
  <span class="h2-sub">An honest accounting of the structural factors</span>

  <p>Gould and Kandra identify several structural factors behind the divergence in wages over the four-decade period. These include the long-stagnant federal minimum wage, declining unionization rates and reduced worker bargaining power, policy decisions that tolerated higher unemployment levels, and the increasing concentration of top-end compensation (including equity, bonuses, and executive pay) that SSA data captures through W-2 reporting.</p>

  <p>This field study does not take a position on the policy prescriptions. Reasonable people disagree about the right mix of minimum wage levels, union law, trade policy, and tax structure. What the data does not permit reasonable disagreement about is the factual record: wages at the top and wages at the bottom moved in different directions, at dramatically different magnitudes, over a sustained and consistent multi-decade period. The divergence predates any particular administration and persisted across economic expansions and contractions alike. That is a structural pattern, not a cyclical anomaly.</p>

