  <h2>The takeaway for anyone who reports on numbers</h2>
  <span class="h2-sub">What this means for how your organization measures things</span>

  <p>The wage inequality data is a useful stress test for how any analyst thinks about summary statistics. When you see an average — any average — it is worth asking four questions.</p>

  <p><strong>What does the distribution actually look like?</strong> Is it roughly normal, skewed, bimodal? If you can only publish one number but the distribution is asymmetric, at minimum acknowledge that the mean and median differ materially.</p>

  <p><strong>Who does the average represent?</strong> In wage data, the average earner does not exist at the average. Most workers earn below mean wages because high earners pull the mean above the median. The same is true in customer revenue data, support ticket volume, and dozens of other business metrics.</p>

  <p><strong>Is the data top-coded or otherwise truncated?</strong> If your CRM caps deal sizes above a threshold, or your survey caps responses, or your reporting tool groups everything above a value into an "other" bucket, you have introduced a top-coding problem into your analysis. High-end concentration becomes structurally invisible.</p>

  <p><strong>What decisions does this number need to support?</strong> If you are making decisions about the bottom half of a distribution — compensation bands, support staffing, churn interventions — a mean that is heavily influenced by the top half of the distribution may be actively misleading. The right statistic depends on the decision, not on convention.</p>

  <div class="callout">
    <p><strong>The broader point:</strong> This is exactly why Aesop Analytics works on metric definition before metric modernization. A dashboard can be technically flawless — correct data, live refresh, clean design — and still return answers to the wrong questions if the metric definitions were built around convenient summary statistics rather than decision-relevant ones. The wage data makes this visible at national scale. It happens in smaller ways in virtually every reporting environment we review.</p>
  </div>

  <p>The story of 40 years of wage inequality is, at its core, a story about what happens when the number being reported — the average — is structurally disconnected from the experience of most of the people in the distribution. That gap is worth noticing wherever it appears.</p>

